My cross-cousin and family live in Noorvik.

column2: Thirty minutes tiŋmiñaqtuq, aasii aputikuaġutikun piŋasut sassaġniġmi.
column3: It's thirty minutes by airplane or three hours by snowmachine.
Are there lots of fish in Noorvik in the Kobuk River?
Yes, there are trout, sheefish, salmon, and northern pike.
Noorvik is on a bluff on the banks of the Kobuk.
Is there another village close to Noorvik?
Yes, Kiana isn't far. It's on the Kobuk too.
How long will you be gone?
In spring we go out to camp on the coast.
It's almost time for geese to arrive.
I will come over when I'm done.
We will go to Larry's place at seven o'clock.
I will return to Fairbanks in the morning.
There will be Iñuit games tonight.

We (always) eat pilot bread with stew.

We make dried fish in summer.

Half-dried salmon are good as leftovers.

I would like to drink some tea.

The men want a hot drink.

Thank you, I haven't eaten Inupiaq food in a long time.
My son here will prepare [and cut] some frozen fish and meat.
When you don't have any Iñupiaq food, you really crave it.
Then I will fix a sack [of food] for you.
It's good to have close friends.
It would be very good indeed to have some berries.
Call me when you plan to come here sometime.
For your information, I will come here again next year.
Good, we will eat together again then.
Hello. Come in, please. Here is a chair.
I have an appointment at one o'clock.
How is Bubba doing in school?

column2: Nakuuruq, kisirrutit nakuaġigai, aglaan iḷaatni agliqisupialaitchuq.
column3: Very good, he likes math, but sometimes does not really like to read.
I read to him at home all the time.
There are books here if you would like to bring some home.
That's okay, we have all kinds of books.
Will you continue to read to him?
Yes, I want him to be able to comprehend his reading.
Very good. I will call or let you know when his reading improves.
You finally came, and what might you be here for?
I'm looking for some small nails.
I want to build a grub box.
Over there by the door [are nails].
And do you have any hinges?
They're across there, behind the brooms.
Do you have cartridges for a twenty-two rifle?
My son is going squirrel hunting tomorrow.
They are in there with the clothing.
There are none. They haven't come in yet.
Here is some strong rope which has just arrived.
There are lots of squirrels at Salluq.
Who made that parka? It has nice trim.
I'd like to buy it for my wife. It's her birthday tomorrow.
Do you know my grandmother Suuyuk? She's my neighbor. She's a good seamstress.
Let me pay now. What is the total cost?
I'm going camping at Pipe Spit tomorrow.
Who else will be going along?
Myself, some children, and some elders.
How will you(3+) go to camp?
How many boats will you(3+) take?
The tents are already there. We all have sleeping bags.
Is the food all ready? Are the boats loaded?
There's lots of food for the journey down on the beach.
What will you(3+) all do at camp?
First, we'll set a net for trout.
When we catch fish, we'll cut them to make dried fish.
And we'll go hunt sea mammals [seals and walruses] when the ice is good.
When we catch sea mammals, we'll butcher them.
We will also make seal oil from the blubber.
When the fish and meat are dry, we will store them.
Are you going to teach the children how to do this?
Yes, the elders want to teach the chikiren.
Call me on the CB radio when you arrive, so that we won't worry.
In the spring, we hunt for wild eggs.
Where do you go to hunt eggs?
My spouse and I are going to the Chamisso Islands.
How do they hunt eggs? Do you have to climb up?

column2: Ii, mayuġnaqtuq, suli iḷaatni qauyaġnaqsisuuruq sialukman.
column3: Yes, you have to climb and sometimes it gets slippery when it rains.
What kinds of eggs are there?
Murres and lesser gulls [smaller than seagulls] nest in the cliffs there.
What else is on the island?
There is sea lovage and wild celery on top of the island; they grow tall.
I would like to go along some time.
Yes, but I will have to watch you closely. It's dangerous when you don't know [the place].
And there is white gravel on the mainland beach.
It's white and they use it when they take the fur off the ugruk hide when making hard soles for mukluks.
First they put it on the fur side [of the maklak bottom] and then they scrape off the fur.
That's great, I've learned something more.
The eggs must be boiled [before they are eaten].
Some people store them in seal oil in pokes.
You can bake a cake using only one egg.
It makes it [the cake] rise a lot.
It's way better than with store-bought eggs.
Wow, they sure eat good food.
We hardly hunt for molting ducks around here.
But there are molting ducks where there are no people.
A long time ago there used to be some in Anigaaq.
There used to be molting ducks there in the grass.
How about now, are they gone?
They are over where there's not much traffic.
Playful expression (Say this while moving your head on one side)

column2: Samma samma, Samma samma,'aa samma samma (2x), Qaupuani izripak!
column3: This is a hand game/song to get baby's attention. Oh there is something. (2x) There are big eyes on his/her forehead!
say this to encourage a baby to stand alone to start walking.

column3: (A song to tickle the baby with hand motioning as flying): Hey Raven up there! What is in your mouth? A little rockfish! Save me a tail! Tickle the baby on his/her tummy.
So cute! [Usually for babies or small children]
Suksraq and Suluk are my parents.
We2 are cross-cousins [meaning our parents are brother and sister].
Who are you? What is your name?
Excuse me. I didn't mean to, I'm sorry.
Don't take it. Leave it alone. Leave her/him alone. [to one person}. (Stop pestering).
So many! Too much! It's a lot!
Scary! [Almost falling or expression of fear].
So poor. [feel bad for the person or situation].
So scary! [Afraid of an angry person or a monster].
Too hot! [As in a building or clothes].
It's no good! Good for nothing!
What in the world is he/she doing?
So beautiful! So pretty! So cute!
Is that okay? Is that it?
Move over! [to three or more people]
No way! [Something believed to be untrue]
So lucky! / I want that too.
The host, as a greeting, says this.
A surprised expression, after not seeing someone for a long time.
What did you come to do?
Go out [to three or more people]
Follow me. Come with me [to one person].
Follow me. Come with me [to three or more people].
Help me [to three or more people].
Take it out [to three or more people].

Touch it. Take it [to three or more people].

Let's go to the basketball game.
What are you going to do?
I want to go to the basketball game.
What do you want to eat?
Where are you staying? Where are you?
How long will you be here?
What are you going to do here?
I'm going to study. (also means I'm going to catechism).
Yes, she/he is alive, but she/he has gotten old.
Yes, in the summer, I will return.
But I don't have seal oil.
How should I do it then?
What kind of hot drink do you want?
How do we say "wolverine" in Inupiaq?
Do you want a hot drink?
I don't want a hot drink.
What is your older sister's Inupiaq name?
What is your younger sibling's English name?
How many children do you have?
I have one son and two daughters.
They go to school in Nome.
No, I am not older than you.
I thought I was older than you.
We'll2 go by boat to pick greens at Tuqsruq. [entry into Imaruk Basin]
Do you have a house in Tuqsruq?
My aunt is a teacher at the school.
How many children do you two have?
How many stores are there in Nome?
They are fishing at the river.
The men are hunting at the sea.
Can you possibly take me up to the airport?
The land here has gotten very green.
In the summer there are lots of mosquitoes here.
What kind of gun do you have?
Do you speak to your grandmother in Inupiaq?
The white person has red hair.
There is a phone at the store.

column2: Naŋizrvik qaaŋalaguu tatpawani samma. Ałłanik niuvanniaġviġaqtuq uptaumi.
column3: There is one up from the hospital. There are other stores in town.
It's up there on Fifth avenue.
Where is the XYZ Center, where elders eat lunch?
It is next to the city office.
The Catholic church is on Steadman Street.
When it becomes warmer, I will fetch some firewood.
When the weather becomes nice, I will take a walk.
When the east wind blows, it is cold.
They will have a dogsled race to Nome.
It is called Iditarod Dog Sled Race.
Joe Garnie used to race by dog sled.
When the weather warms up, some people will go camping.
They usually go camping on the beach at Cape Wooley.
In the spring, the men that are able to, will go hunting.
They went hunting for seals when it was good weather.
He is kayaking even though it is windy.
They went hunting for bearded seals when it was not so cold.
They brought food along to eat for their trip.
There are six children in the hall.
Do you have fifteen dollars? (dollar bills)
Seventeen people are going to Utqiaġvik.
How many reindeer are there? Eighteen.
How many people are working over there? Nineteen.
Her mother turned forty on her birthday.
One hundred people arrived by plane.
More than a thousand people live in Nome.
Sinruk as in "Sinrock Mary" or Sinuk as in Sinuk River
My daughter went to Utqiaġvik yesterday.
The Chukchii people came to dance.
When will you travel to Cape Nome?
I won't be going to Shishmaref, I'll go to Teller.
What will you do in Teller?
No, he/she will take care of the children.
Do you have family at Teller?
My cross-cousin and family live in Teller.
How far is it from Nome?

column2: Silakuaqsuutigun thirty minutes, Karagun'aa 2 hours ittuq.
column3: Thirty minutes by plane, and two hours by car.
Are there lots of fish at Teller?
Yes, there are salmon, tomcods and smelts.
Teller is at the Grantley Harbor.
Is there another village near Teller?

column2: Ii'ii, Sitaisaq qanittuurauruq. Port Clearance Bay-mi ittuq.
column3: Yes, Brevig Mission is nearby. It is on Port Clearance Bay.
In springtime the men go out hunting.
In summer we fish and it is hot.
In early autumn we pick berries.
What time do we head to school?
It is time to go home.
It is time to go home.
It's almost time for school to be out.
It's almost time for geese to arrive.
I will come over when I am done.
We will go to Marilyn's place at five o'clock.
In the morning, I will return to Fairbanks.
There will be traditional dancing later.
I eat raisons all the time.
Assaaluk whips a traditional berry mix.
Do you eat traditional berry mix?
I want to buy some bread.
Do you want to eat some bread?
We ate dried meat for dinner.
We make dried meat in the spring.
I ate boiled half-dried salmon with willow greens.
Boiled half-dried salmon make good leftovers.
I want some tea to drink.
The men want a hot drink.
Is there still coffee in the coffee maker?
I will make boiled fish in the cooking pot.
They are fishing in the river.
They fish for tomcods in the spring and in the fall.
Tom and his crew went caribou hunting.

Jaegers are scary when they are nesting.

Auklets are plentiful on King Island.
Canadian goose are plentiful at the lake

Mr. Green is the principal at the school.
They are learning how to work the computers.
You finally came, what are you looking for?
I want to buy some calico fabric.
I wanted to make a parka for my daughter.
Over there by the clothes are calico fabrics. (for cloth parkies)
I will also buy some groceries.
My mother is also buying clothes.
What kind of supplies were you looking for?
My older brother wanted some nails.
Oh, what else is he making?
He wanted to make a grub box.
Are there cartridges for a twenty-two rifle?
My son wanted some to go hunting for squirrels.
How about the rubber boots, where are they?
There are no more, and the things I ordered haven't arrived yet.
Who made your parka? You have very nice parka.
I wanted to buy a parka for my wife. Her birthday is tomorrow.
Do you know my mother? She is a good seamstress.
Let me pay for it. How much is it?

I wore a new calico for dancing.

Listen to him/her and be respectful to the one speaking.
